{"/service/ndnp/iune/batch_iune_cinnabar_ver01/data/sn94054571/00332897962/1949033001/0525.xml":{"full_text":"PRETTY MARCH WEDDING\nMrs. Gregory Rice\nPhoto by John Paul. Cut Courtesy Waukegan News-Sun.\nMiss Elizabeth Norris Me\nhaffey and E. Gregory Rice\nwere united in holy wedlock at\na pretty March wedding in\nZion Chapel on the evening of\nMarch 5th, 1949. Overseer An\nton Darms was the officiating\nclergyman.\nMiss Mehaffey is the eldest\ndaughter of Mr. and Mrs. John\nA. MeHaffey of Zion Hotel,\nZion, Illinois, while the bride\u2019s\nhusband is the younger son of\nMr. and Mrs. Rollin Rice of\nToulon, Illinois.\nThe Chapel altar was deli\ncately decorated with baskets\nof white glads grouped be\ntween graceful palms and\nferns; while the candelabra on\nthe altar, as well as those\nwhich flanked the aisle, were\nfestooned with streamers of\nwhite glads in ivy, each mount\ned by a large white satin bow.\nThe bride entered on the\narm of her father in an ivory\nslipper satin gown with illu\nsion neckline, and a full length\ntrain. Her three-tier illusion\nveil fell from a tiara of satin\nand pearls. Her bridal flowers\nconsisted of a shower cascade\nof gardenias and garlands of\nwhite hyacinth blossoms and\nivy.\nThe maid of honor and the\nbridesmaids entered in gowns\nof green faille, with yellow\nlace hats and mitts, carrying\ngarlands of yellow jonquil and\nivy.\nThe maid of honor Miss\nEdna Thomas of McKees Rock,\nPa., a schoolmate of the bride'\nat Juanita College, had flown\nin from Pennsylvania and had\nbeen met by the bride on\nThursday afternoon in Chica\ngo.\nThe bridesmaids were Gloria\nMcElroy-Robinson and Peggy\nDriscoll.\nThe junior bridesmaid, the\nbride\u2019s youngest sister, Diane\nPrice Mehaffey, was attired in\nI an exact duplicate of the\nbridesmaid\u2019s gowns and car\nried a Colonial bouquet of jon\nquils and white sweet peas.\nThe groom entered escorted\nby his best man Wendell\nWitte; his other attendants\nwere Edward Mehaffey and\nClay Appenheimer.\nThe ring bearer was Julian\nEmanuelson, Jr.\nAfter the candle lighters\u2014\nLaurette Emanuuelson and\nGloriette Peterson\u2014had lit the\ncandelabra, Edward Mehaffey,\nthe bride\u2019s brother, sang \u201cAl\nways\u201d by Irving Berlin.\nThe bride was met at the al\ntar steps by the groom, and,\nbefore they ascended, the\nbride\u2019s sister, Joan Mehaffey\nSimpson, sang \u201cStars in Your\nEyes.\u201d\nOverseer Anton Darms had\nbeen requested to use a double\nring service. After the minis\nter\u2019s final prayer William L.\nSimpson sang the \u201cLord\u2019s\nPrayer.\u201d\nThe musical selections, the\nwedding march and recession\nal, as well as music while the\nguests were gathering, was\nplayed on the Auditorium or\ngan by Evangeline Beem. The\nsound of the organ was brought\nto the Chapel by electrical am\nplification, which musical ef\nfect was. very appropriate.\nMrs. Beem also played during\nthe reception at Zion Hotel.\nIn order to make a lasting\nremembrance of the ceremony,\nthe entire service was recorded\nby Paul Peters assisted by Les\nter Wright\u2019s p. m. system.\nAt the conclusion of the wed\nding service, the bridal party\nreceived the congratulations\nand well wishes of the relatives\nand friends.\nThe bride\u2019s mother wore a\ngown of black, with teal blue\naccessories; corsage of red ros\nes. The groom\u2019s mother wore\nlight blue crepe and a corsage\nof pink roses.\nThe gowns were the bride\u2019s\ndesigns, with detail and exe\ncution by Mrs. O. C. Tanner,\nbridal gown expert; while the\nfloral decorations were the art\nwork of Mrs. Anna Fisher.\nJohn Paul, photographer,\ntook group and individual pic\ntures of the bride and bridal,\nparty. Candid shots were tak\nen during the evening.\nThe bridal party and 300\nguests then enjoyed a social\nevening at Zion Hotel Gold\nand Blue Rooms, where the\nbride cut the four-tier wedding\ncake. After the initial cut by\nthe bride of the wedding cake,\nMrs. Wilbur Ball served it as\nthe guests partook of refresh\nments; Mrs. Harry Walton and\nMrs. Donald Erickson poured.\nThe bridal table was beautiful\nly decorated with a double\nring center piece and tinted\ngreen and yellow gardenias in\nColonial bouquet holders and\nivy, carrying out the bride\u2019s\ncolor scheme. There were also\nbouquets of jonquils.\nAs the guests entered the\nBlue Room of the hotel they\nwere requested by Mrs. Virgil\nBurkey to sign the Guest Book.\nThe wedding gifts were ar\nranged by Miriam and Betty\nEmanuelson, Mrs. John D. Tho\nmas and Mrs. Leslie Rueckert.\nThe bride is a graduate of\nZion-Benton Township High\nSchool, class of \u201942, and attend\ned Juanita College at Hufit\nington, Pa., for two and a half\nyears, as well as Northwestern\nUniversity. The groom grad\nuated from the Toulon High\nSchool, then served with the\nUnited States Army during the\nlate war, and has been special\nizing in agriculture at the Uni\nversity of Illinois, Peoria divi\nsion.\nThe young couple enjoyed\na late snack with friends at the\nDrake Hotel, Chicago, and\nthen left for Florida on their\nhoneymoon. There they plan\nned on greeting relatives and\nfriends along the east coast\nand going south as far as Key\nWest, Florida. In Florida they\nwere entertained by the Jos\neph Emanuelsons, the Wm.\nMatselbobas and Mrs. Ida R.\nVoliva. On their return, they\nwill be at home at Toulon, 111.\nThe various details were at\ntended to by James Anderson,\nDonald Robinson and Virgil\nBurkey under the guidance of\nCarl Huth, chief usher.\nThe bride, having been a\nZion resident all her life, has\nmany relatives living in town,\nand therefore they are not list\ned in the following group, as\nthe names are principally of\nthe out-of-town guests:\nBride\u2019s Sister:\nMrs. Joan Mehaffey-Simp\nson and husband Wm. of Ev\nanston, 111.\nBride\u2019s Aunts and Uncles:\nMrs. E. A. Chambers of Wa\nterloo, Iowa; Mrs. H. T. Dris\ncoll of Waukegan, 111.; Mr. and\nMrs. M. E. Raso and daughter\nMarilyn of Chicago, 111.; Mr.\nand Mrs. T. A. Emanuelson\nand son Robert of Gary, Ind.\nThe Groom's Parents and\nBrother:\nMr. and Mrs. Rollin Rice and\nthe groom\u2019s brother Rollin H.\nRice of Toulon, Illinois. While\nthey came to the wedding, the\ngroom\u2019s uncle, Harley Rice,\nstayed at home caring for their\nlive stock.\nThe Groom\u2019s Aunts:\nMiss Nellie Rice of Wyo\nming, was glad she made the\ntrip east.\nCousins of the Bride:\nMrs. Preston Hickey came\nall the way from Maine; Mrs.\nBertha Richards of Harvey, 111.\nand Hollywood, Galif.; Mrs.\nJohn Winkleman of Chicago,\n111., Mrs. John Kunze of Har\nvey, 111., and Miss Eloise Ben\nnett, who flew up from Flori\ndat to be present. Mr. and Mrs.\nEdwin Hunt and daughter\ndrove up from Harvey, 111.\nGroom\u2019s Cousins:\nMr. and Mrs. Duane Moose\nof Volante, Pa. They made the\nround trip by train.\nFriends of the Bride:\nMiss Edna Thomas, the maid\nof honor, who flew in from Mc\nkees Rock, Pa.\nMr. and Mrs. R. F. Kraft of\nEvanston, 111.; Mr. and Mrs. S.\nE. Burkey and daughter Jo\nanne of Wadsworth, 111.; Dr.\nand Mrs. Vern S. Hall, Miss\nIrene Benetis and Mr. and Mrs.\nL. E. Swank of Waukegan, 111.;\nMrs. J. A. Whitcomb and\ndaughters, the Misses Mildred\nand Thelma Whitcomb of Ke\nnosha, Wis.; Mr. and Mrs. Jar\ned Neal, Miss Josephine Mick\nus, and Mr. and Mrs. Helmut\nTeichner and daughters, and\nMr. and Mrs. E. L. Sourby and\ndaughter Carol, all of Chica\ngo, Illinois; and Mr. and Mrs.\nSeth Hultenius of Winthrop\nHarbor, 111.\nFriends of the Groom:\nClay Appenheimer and Mr.\nand Mrs. Wendell Witte, Don\nand George Heaton, Gene\nHarvey, Mr. and Mrs. William\nTurnbull, Joan McManus,\nJane McWilliam, Mrs. Leta\nHutchens and daughter Doris,\nall of Toulon, Illinois. Irma\nNelson of Knoxville, Illinois.\nMrs. Gladys Edwards of Chi\ncago.\nHome over the week-end\nwas Miss Carlene Mischler, of\nStephens College at Columbia,\nMissouri. She was accompanied\nby her roommate, Miss Mary\nAnn DeBord of ElPaso, Texas,\nas Carlene\u2019s guest.\nAPRIL\n3, 10, 17, and 24\nMAY\n1, 8, 15, 22, 29\nJUNE\n5, 12, 19, 26\nAll Seats Reserved!","height":"19221","width":"13617"}}
